  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over time:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) in the US\n- Initial focus on reporting large cash transactions\n- Limited international cooperation\n\n2. International Developments\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Developed global anti-money laundering standards\n- Created recommendations for international compliance\n\n3. Key Legislative Milestones\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Enhanced financial institution reporting requirements\n- Increased international information sharing\n- Stricter customer identification protocols\n\n4. Expanded Legal Frameworks\n- Enhanced due diligence requirements\n- More comprehensive Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n- Broader definition of financial crimes\n\n5. Technology-Driven Innovations\n- Digital transaction monitoring\n- Advanced risk assessment algorithms\n- Cryptocurrency regulation\n- Enhanced cross-border tracking mechanisms\n\n6. Recent Trends\n- More comprehensive beneficial ownership regulations\n- Greater emphasis on cryptocurrency and digital asset tracking\n- Increased transparency requirements\n- Stronger international collaboration\n\nEach legislative evolution has aimed to create more robust systems for detecting and preventing financial crimes.",
